Angelman Syndrome Awareness Day. 
I know that every day is a day for something, but today is one where we get to honor all the beautiful & loving angels that have the rare genetic disorder known as Angelman Syndrome (AS).

Juliette and I have such a rockstar of a daughter, Lou. Her dedication to progression, relentless endurance, and never-ending love amazes me. Lou has Angelman Syndrome, which makes life way harder in many ways, but through her eyes that see the world differently, I see so much enlightenment; she always lives in the moment, she is wholly present, and she reacts to almost everything with love & laughter.

I learn so much from Lou and her perma-stoked ways. Like all Angelman kids, she faces many challenges that “normal people” never have to consider. Her body doesn’t function like ours, nor does her mind. She’s missing a tiny piece of a chromosome, which would create a protein in her brain; this protein helps the brain function normally. Without this protein (UBE3A), her brain operates quite differently. Having AS creates developmental delays, significant physical challenges, difficulties comprehending language, and makes Lou nonverbal; it also comes with epilepsy, many things that make life much more complicated. 
But she doesn’t let any of this stop her from giving 100%. I have spent many years in the gym training, working to overcome my next hurdle, and now I do the same with her. Together we do physical, occupational, and Speech therapy daily. Lou does not take a single pharmaceutical, instead, she is on a ketogenic diet to mitigate seizures. Incredibly, she has been without a single seizure since we began this approach. 

All the challenges become opportunities; Lou sees the world in such a psychedelic way; she doesn’t care so much about language; she feels and reacts to energy & vibes. She doesn’t care about what’s cool and not; she’s just happy to be here and ecstatic to love. 

Lou is always present and ready to love, forgive, admire, laugh, and play. She is the physical manifestation of STOKE!

2020 Aloha Award Winner @nigel_savel & his organization, the @9milesproject 

This is the last week to nominate someone for their chance to win this years @alohaaward 

The winner gets $10,000 for their organization and a free trip to @namotuisland 

I want to celebrate some of the fantastic people who have won the Aloha Award. They are so incredibly heartwarming and such inspiring people. 

If you know someone who embodies the aloha spirit, check out the link in my profile to nominate them. 

A bit more about Nigel: 
 Born and bred in the beautiful city of Cape Town, South Africa, Nigel Savel started surfing at 9Miles Beach in Strandfontein at the age of 11. The ocean was a place of tranquility where he could switch off from any worries and allowed him to escape the surrounding dangers and social ills in his community. 
As an adult, he realised that children in the surrounding informal settlements had few positive role models and were being lured into illegal and anti-social activities. He knew first-hand that surfing, combined with mentorship, was a powerful combination for transforming lives. Motivated by his love for surfing, Nigel, along with his wife Sher’Neil, started the 9Miles Project in 2013 with the vision of uplifting and empowering vulnerable communities.  Surfing is used as a catalyst to engage and entice vulnerable, at-risk youth to the project and to teach them discipline, determination and life skills. The organisation has, in seven years, grown from 7 to 100 children and offers safe spaces, structured afterschool and literacy programmes, and holistic community support and skills development programmes in three coastal locations in South Africa.

Lesson #532: don’t be a Mr. Big Stuff; just ride the big stuff.

This past year, while tackling the infamous Jaws in every which way I could, I had a small epiphany; I realized that I was finally coming back to who I was as a kid. Perhaps it happened because every day, I’m either on the water, and then I subsequently go home to play with my kids, or I am in the water teaching my kids to swim, kite, and surf. As a result of this simple daily practice, I was awoken to the fundamental purpose of my existence: it is only to have fun. 

Several months ago, while emptying an old storage unit, I came across some decades-old footage of myself as a middle schooler, deeply embroiled in my life as a budding professional kitesurfer. The only thing that mattered to me at that point was being the guy, out on the water, with the biggest smile on his face. 

A little later, as I entered my teenage years, I found myself thriving under the pressure of competition, winning multiple world titles, a high which created a cycle of adrenaline addiction with seemingly high rewards. I became obsessed with being the most extreme athlete in this niche sport. The bigger the risk, the wilder the stunt, the more accolades. It built a fire within me that enabled me to flourish under the most stressful of circumstances. Now, I wanted to be the guy that won every single discipline of kitesurfing imaginable, the guy who would do any and every trick that the freestylers would, but way higher... and with a kiteloop! The guy who would go out at the gnarliest waves in the world even when the best surfers thought it was reckless. The guy who people looked at and thought, “Man, he’s crazy.”

It’s wild how quickly life can change. I just had one of the most stressful weeks of my life, if not the most. 

I love posting regularly here but I have a hard time multitasking and I like to be real/authentic on here. So, when my mind is somewhere else, I just don’t have it in me to post or really respond to much on my phone. (Sorry if you are on the list of people that I haven’t gotten back to) 

I’m not sharing this to seek sympathy or attention. I just realized how many people I’ve seen go through something similar or even more challenging, and I guess I want to say …holy…moly. 

Watching your child struggle and worrying that you are watching them go through something potentially causing permanent damage is an indescribable and terrible experience. 

I’ve never been tested like that before. So clearly, I see how perfect life was before this; everything was flawless just a few days prior. Yes, I wish I could go back, but there is no going back, only forward and trying as hard as we can to make the right or at least the least wrong decision. 

As many of you know, my daughter Lou has Angelman syndrome. Seizures are a part of AS, and we have managed her seizures pretty well, but last week the wheels came off the bus, and Lou ended up being stuck in a state where she was having hundreds of short seizures, multiple per minute. We spent many days at a hospital in California trying to figure out the best way to stabilize her, and it was far from a simple/straightforward process. 

The reason this happened was because we decided to work a bit with western medicine as opposed to just following our diet/lifestyle and supplement approach with Lou. This quickly spiraled into a complete rabbit hole of commitment to that ideology. Instead of it helping her it totally unraveled her health and well-being.
